column7: plural

Possibly a derivation of PS *oarpe?ne? 'female cousin' (> Skolt vuä?rben-) (Lehtiranta 2001: 94–95) ~ Finnish orpana and as such ultimately a loan from PII *Hárbha- 'small, weak, young' (Holopainen 2019: 168–170).

A derivative of puä?res 'old' (< PS *poare?s 'old'), which itself has been thought to be a Indo-Iranian borrowing, cf. PII *parHa-s 'ferner; jenseitig; früher; später; fremd, feinlich' (Holopainen 2019: 189). Front vocalic Udm. pere? and Komi përï? are parallel borrowings (Pre-Permic *pärä-). Perhaps Skolt is a calque of Finnic vanhemmat 'parents' (lit. "olders").
As a kinship term a PS innovation
A diminutive derivative of pä?rnn 'son; child'
Cognate with Finnish ylkä 'young man; groom' (obsolete).

PS *a?kko? 'grandmother' is a derivative of PS *a?kke? 'old woman' that is in traditional sources thought to be a cognate with Finnic *akka 'old woman' (Lehtiranta 2001: 12–13; SSA: 64–65). The vowel correspondence is atypical of inherited vocabulary, PU *a-a yields PS *uo-e?. As such the underlying Sami word has to be Finnic borrowing (Aikio 2009: 244). Similar words denoting female relatives are common in world's languages.

According to SSA Skolt kaav (and related Sami words) is a borrowing from Finnish kave 'created being; human; girl, maiden', which in turn has been thought to be a Germanic borrowing *skapi-z (OHG skaf) (LägLoS: 68–69). The Finnish kave is obsolete. The discrepancy in meaning between Finnish and Sami is striking.

The Sami word is thought to include an obscure derivational suffix. It is perhaps noteworthy that PU *ana/ëna 'mother-in-law' is not attested as such anywhere in Uralic, only in derivations like this Sami item or in the copulative compound *a/ëna-ëpp? 'parents-in-law'.
Moshnikoff 2021 defines the word as 'brother's wife, paternal/maternal uncle's wife', according to Pelto 1962 the word is of older brother's wife.
According to Pelto 1962 vivv is also 'younger brother's wife'
older sister's husband', self-reciprocal pair with maakkâv
